SIMPLE: manual
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Manual
<hw>Man"u*al</hw> <pr>(m⟦acr⟧n"⟦usl⟧*⟦ait⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>manuel</ets>, F. <ets>manuel</ets>, L.
<ets>manualis</ets>, fr. <ets>manus</ets> hand; prob. akin to AS.
<ets>mund</ets> hand, protection, OHG. <ets>munt</ets>, G.
<ets>m⟦uum⟧nd</ets>el a ward, vor<ets>mund</ets> guardian, Icel.
<ets>mund</ets> hand. Cf. <er>Emancipate</er>, <er>Legerdemain</er>,
<er>Maintain</er>, <er>Manage</er>, <er>Manner</er>, <er>Manure</er>,
<er>Mound</er> a hill.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the
hand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Performed by a person using physical as contrasted
with <contr>mental</contr> effort; <as>as, <ex>manual</ex>
labor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Done or made by the hand. In some contexts,
contrasted with <contr>automatic</contr> or
<contr>mechanical</contr>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Manual</xex> and ocular
examination.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Tatham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Manual exercise</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <cd>the
exercise by which soldiers are taught the use of their muskets and other
arms.</cd> -- <col><b>Seal manual</b></col>, <cd>the impression of a
seal worn on the hand as a ring.</cd> -- <col><b>Sign manual</b></col>.
<cd>See under <er>Sign</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manual</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Manual
<hw>Man"u*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>manuel</ets>, LL. <ets>manuale</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small book, such as may be
carried in the hand, or conveniently handled; a handbook; specifically,
the service book of the Roman Catholic Church.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>manual</qex> of laws, styled the Confessor's Laws.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A keyboard of an organ or
harmonium for the fingers, as distinguished from the pedals; a clavier,
or set of keys.</def> <rj><au>Moore (Encyc. of Music).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A prescribed exercise in the
systematic handing of a weapon; <as>as, the <ex>manual</ex> of arms; the
<ex>manual</ex> of the sword; the <ex>manual</ex> of the piece (cannon,
mortar, etc.).</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manual alphabet</ent>⟦br⟧
